{
  "query": "What design and placement factors influence the successful use of bat boxes by bats?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across multiple replicated studies and reviews, bat box use and occupancy were influenced by both design and placement factors: bats used black boxes more than grey, white, or wooden boxes; occupancy was sometimes higher in larger boxes; concrete boxes had higher occupancy than wooden boxes; resin boxes became occupied more quickly than wood in one study; Indiana bats preferred rocket boxes over wooden boxes or bark\u2011mimic roosts; boxes with two or multiple compartments/chambers had higher or differentiated use (including breeding colonies using standard and 4\u20135 chamber boxes, with individuals using flat boxes); different species selected different designs; and trunk\u2011simulating boxes were used by 100% of bats in one study (1024). Placement factors included orientation and/or sunlight exposure affecting occupancy in several studies (with one study finding no effect); mixed results for height (some studies finding effects and others none); higher occupancy on buildings than on trees in two studies; higher occupancy in certain habitat contexts (e.g., farm forestry vs native forest; pine stands vs mixed deciduous; forest fragments vs pasture); higher occupancy when boxes were installed where bats were known to roost previously; and greater likelihood of occupancy when a larger number of boxes were installed across a site (1024).",
